|}

== The Four-Rank System in Japan ==

Japan introduced the Four-Rank System during the 7th century based on Tang models. Under the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝律令|12=draft}} and {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令|12=draft}}, it established four roles: {{lang-ja|長官}} (chief officer), {{lang-ja|次官}} (deputy officer), {{lang-ja|判官}} (adjudicator), and {{lang-ja|主典}} (administrator). Unlike Tang practices, Japan did not adopt the "Three-Adjudication System."

{{Four-Rank Table}}

== Four-Rank System in Silla ==

In {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|12=draft}}, positions like {{lang-ja|令}} (chief) and {{lang-ja|佐}} (assistant) existed, though exact correlations remain speculative due to scarce records.

== Other Applications ==

During the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}}, Japan revived the Four-Rank framework under restorationist policies. However, modernized names and roles reflected unique adaptations.

