''''Four-Rank System''' ({{lang-ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan}}, {{Transliteration|rom=Shitōkan, Historical kana usage: Shitōkwan}}), or the '''Four-Rank Official System''' ({{lang-ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan制}}), refers to the hierarchical organization of key officials within each bureau under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Originating in China's {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it served as the foundation of an elaborate {{ill|bureaucratic system|ja|官僚|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Japan adopted the Four-Rank System alongside the implementation of the Ritsuryō system.

== Overview ==

The Four-Rank System consists of four grades: '''chief officer''', '''deputy officer''', '''adjudicating officer''', and '''administrative officer'''. Their respective duties were outlined in the Ritsuryō codes.

== The Four-Rank System in Tang China ==

{{ill|Tang dynasty|ja|唐|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Ritsuryō administration featured a hierarchy with chief officers, assistant adjudicators, adjudicators, and administrative officers. Additional roles, such as inspectors ({{lang-ja|検勾官}}, {{Transliteration|rom=Kenkyūkan}}), ensured accountability. While central offices had diverse titles, regional offices adopted more standardized terminology.

In Tang law:
- Fourth-Rank officers (administrative) managed clerical tasks and archives without influencing decisions.
- Adjudicators (third Rank) held decision-making powers and forwarded cases to deputy officers.
- Deputy officers (second Rank) reviewed and finalized decisions.
- Chief officers conducted the ultimate review.

This process, termed the "Three-Adjudication System" ({{lang-ja|三判制}}, {{Transliteration|rom=Sanpansei}}), emphasized hierarchical reviews.<ref>Naito Kenkichi, "Study of Tang Dynasty Official Documents," *Chinese Legal History Research*, Yuhikaku, 1963.</ref>

{{ill|Inner-stream officials|ja|流内官|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (chief to adjudicators) differed significantly in Rank and status from outer-stream officials (administrative).

; Tang Four-Rank Table
{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Institution !! Chief Officer !! Deputy Officer !! Adjudicating Officer !! Inspector !! Administrative Officer
|-
| {{ill|Shangshu Sheng|ja|尚書省|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Shangshu Ling|ja|尚書令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || Pushe || Cheng || Langzhong || Zhushi
|-
| {{ill|Six Ministries|ja|六部|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || Shangshu || Shilang || Langzhong || Langzhong || Zhushi
|-
| {{ill|Menxia Sheng|ja|門下省|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || Shizhong || Huangmen Shilang || Jishi Zhong || Luzhi || Zhushi
|}

== The Four-Rank System in Japan ==

Japan introduced the Four-Rank System during the 7th century based on Tang models. Under the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝律令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it established four roles: {{lang-ja|長官}} (chief officer), {{lang-ja|次官}} (deputy officer), {{lang-ja|判官}} (adjudicator), and {{lang-ja|主典}} (administrator). Unlike Tang practices, Japan did not adopt the "Three-Adjudication System."

{{Four-Rank Table}}

== Four-Rank System in Silla ==

In {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, positions like {{lang-ja|令}} (chief) and {{lang-ja|佐}} (assistant) existed, though exact correlations remain speculative due to scarce records.

== Other Applications ==

During the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan revived the Four-Rank framework under restorationist policies. However, modernized names and roles reflected unique adaptations.

